entry.title: Fix BackgroundURLLoader's issue in handling redirect
entry.content:
Currently there is a bug in BackgroundURLLoader that if a request

was redirected, and the request is canceld by destructing the

BackgroundURLLoader before Context::OnReceivedRedirect() is called,

FollowRedirectCallback is destructed in the main thread. The

FollowRedirectCallback was created in the backgroud thread by

ResourceRequestSender::OnReceivedRedirect(), and it must be destructed

in the background thread. When DCHECK is enable,

DCHECK_CALLED_ON_VALID_SEQUENCE() in ThreadCheckingCallbackWrapper's

destructor fails.



To fix this issue, this CL changes RequestClient::OnReceivedRedirect()

to wrap the FollowRedirectCallback with a OnTaskRunnerDeleter as

a std::unique_ptr.

So the FollowRedirectCallback must be destructed in the background

thread.



Bug: 1379780

entry.content:
There are thousands of calls to the ExceptionState::Throw* methods,

sufficiently many that indirecting via the vtable in the caller adds

entry.title: LinkPreview: Polish activation code
entry.content:
This patch rewrites the preview activation code to operate via

the PageImpl class to follow the prerendering activation design.



We can pass all relevant RenderViewHosts to perform activation

also on subframes hosted by different RenderViews. In this CL,

we are passing only the main frame's RenderViewHost yet though.



With this change, we can relax the capability controls via the

common activation code path.



Also, this change reveals an existing bug that the capability

control wasn't applied correctly if the initially created

RenderFrameHost is reused for the preview navigation.

This is because the initial RenderFrameHost is created before

WebContents::Create() returns, and WebContents::SetDelegate()

call is too late to notify the preview mode to the initial

RenderFrameHost.

To resolve this issue, this patch modifies

WebContents::CreateParams to store WebContentsDelegate and set it

immediately after the WebContents instance creation.

entry.title: [text-autospace] Sync width to `CharacterPositionData`
entry.content:
When applying auto-spacing, this patch synchronizes

`ShapeResult::width_` to `CharacterPositionData::width_` if

the `ShapeResult` has `CharacterPositionData`.



They need to be in sync for `CachedOffsetForPosition` and

`CachedPositionForOffset` to work correctly, which are used

by `ShapingLineBreaker`.



While fixing this, tests discovered a bug where

`ApplyTextAutoSpacingCore` doesn't add the spacing to `width_`

for the RTL code path. Instead of fixing it, this patch

changes `RecalcCharacterPositions` to update both `width_`s.



`ApplyTextAutoSpacing` always calls `RecalcCharacterPositions`.

The code that adjusts `width_` in `ApplyTextAutoSpacingCore`

is thus removed.

entry.title: Revert "Add per-test-case tracing and archive trace output for web_tests"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8070e3362c2f9efc3ae15b61ecc235acf71b9d52.



Reason for revert: Broke results.html.

> Uncaught SyntaxError: missing ) after argument list - results.html:1039



Original change's description:

> Add per-test-case tracing and archive trace output for web_tests

>

> The existing --enable-tracing argument to run_web_tests.py generates a

> trace that spans the life of the test binary process. Due to the way

> this flag is turned into driver flags, this forces the test runner to

> restart the test binary after every test case. There are a few

> problems:

>

> - There is no way to specify --enable-tracing on a per-test basis.

>

> - Restarting the test binary after every test case is extremely slow.

>

> - Restarting the test binary after every test may suppress failures

> caused by stale state left in the test binary after a test case.

> Historically, this is a significant source of bugs.

>

> - The trace file is not archived by the test runner.

>

> This patch tries to fix all four problems. The trace file created by

> --enable-tracing is now archived. Additionally, the new flag

> --enable-per-test-tracing allows tracing to be enabled on a per-test

> basis; it does not force additional test binary restarts; and its

> output is also archived. The two flags can be used in combination

> without any problem.

>

> The new python class variable Port.TESTS_TO_TRACE offers a convenient

> way to generate profiles for a limited set of tests when running on

> the bots.

>

entry.title: [iOS blink] Add kPreventResizingContentsForTesting flag...
entry.content:
for content_browsertests and web-platform-tests.



In a previous CL [1], the default size for tests was changed from

800x600 to 980x735 due to the issue with shrinking controls when

tests didn't provide a viewport meta.

To enable this change only for content_browsertests,

- Add switch |kPreventResizingContentsForTesting|

- Apply |kPreventResizingContentsForTesting| only for

content_browsertests



For web-platform-tests, the recommended viewport size for web-platform-tests as 800x600 for conciseness, as stated in [3].

When rebaselining expectations for iOS in web-platform-tests,

it became concerns that a significant number of expectations generated

entry.title: Fix test LacrosExtensionAppsControllerTest.LaunchPinnedApp
entry.content:
This fixes a race condition in the mentioned test.



Key steps in the test:

1. Test (Lacros) launches the app and waits until the shelf (Ash) knows

about the app.

2. Test pins the app.

3. Test closes the app window.

4. Test waits until Ash says the window is gone.

5. Test launches the app via the shelf (Ash).

6. Test waits for the app window.



The test occasionally times out in step (6). Here's what happens in

these runs:



When step (4) is executed, exo has not yet processed the Ash part of

step (3). In fact, exo has not even shown the window from step (1) as

it's still waiting for content. Because the window isn't shown, step (4)

immediately finishes. In step (5) the invisible window is found,

bypassing the actual launch of the app. Instead, Ash tries to activate

the existing window, but there is still no content. Moreover, between

(5) and (6) Ash performs the window destruction triggered via Wayland

in step (3), so the test times out in step (6).



Fix this by waiting for the app window before step (3).

entry.title: Add per-test-case tracing and archive trace output for web_tests
entry.content:
The existing --enable-tracing argument to run_web_tests.py generates a

trace that spans the life of the test binary process. Due to the way

this flag is turned into driver flags, this forces the test runner to

restart the test binary after every test case. There are a few

problems:



- There is no way to specify --enable-tracing on a per-test basis.



- Restarting the test binary after every test case is extremely slow.



- Restarting the test binary after every test may suppress failures

caused by stale state left in the test binary after a test case.

Historically, this is a significant source of bugs.



- The trace file is not archived by the test runner.



This patch tries to fix all four problems. The trace file created by

--enable-tracing is now archived. Additionally, the new flag

--enable-per-test-tracing allows tracing to be enabled on a per-test

basis; it does not force additional test binary restarts; and its

output is also archived. The two flags can be used in combination

without any problem.



The new python class variable Port.TESTS_TO_TRACE offers a convenient

way to generate profiles for a limited set of tests when running on

the bots.
